# Canonical Write Architecture (audric/web)

> **Status:** SHIPPED. SPEC 7 v0.4 (2026-05-01) lands the canonical-write contract; v0.7e Phase 5 (2026-05-22) deleted `apps/web` and the canonical path now lives in `apps/web-v2/app/api/transactions/prepare/route.ts`. The current write tool surface is 8 tools (post-S.245 + S.269 + S.277): `save_deposit`, `withdraw`, `borrow`, `repay_debt`, `send_transfer`, `claim_rewards`, `harvest_rewards`, `swap_execute`. References below to `pay_api`, `volo_stake`, `volo_unstake`, `save_contact`, `create_invoice`, and `apps/web/__tests__/` paths are historical (pre-deletion); the canonical-write principle they teach still holds.

## The contract

Every Audric Enoki-sponsored write ‚Äî chat-agent writes, MPP `services/prepare`, diagnostics ‚Äî MUST go through one canonical compose primitive: **`composeTx(steps)` in `@t2000/sdk`**. The fragment-appender pattern (one `add{Tool}ToTx` per write tool) is the implementation; `composeTx` is the canonical entry-point.

The intent: same drift-impossible-by-construction guarantee the read-side `getPortfolio()` collapse delivered in April 2026, applied to the write side.

## Canonical files

| Concern | Function | File |
|---|---|---|
| Canonical write composer | `composeTx({ sender, steps, sponsoredContext? })` | `@t2000/sdk` ‚Üí `packages/sdk/src/composeTx.ts` |
| Fragment-appender registry | `WRITE_APPENDER_REGISTRY: Record<WriteToolName, AppenderFn>` | Same file |
| Auto-derived allow-list | `deriveAllowedAddressesFromPtb(tx)` | Same file (helper) |
| Per-protocol appenders | `addSaveToTx`, `addWithdrawToTx`, `addBorrowToTx`, `addRepayToTx`, `addSendToTx`, `addSwapToTx`, `addClaimRewardsToTx` (Volo `addStakeVSuiToTx`/`addUnstakeVSuiToTx` removed in S.323) | `@t2000/sdk` ‚Üí `packages/sdk/src/protocols/*.ts` + `wallet/send.ts` |
| Shared Enoki sponsor wrapper | `sponsorViaEnoki({ txKindBytes, sender, allowedAddresses, jwt })` | `audric/apps/web/lib/sponsor.ts` (NEW in SPEC 7 v0.4) |

## Why this is non-negotiable

In April 2026 the **read-side** had five different code paths computing wallet USD with five different bugs. The fix collapsed every read into one `getPortfolio()` canonical fetcher. Drift became impossible by construction. See `audric-canonical-portfolio.mdc`.

The **write-side audit** for SPEC 7 v0.4 surfaced the same structural pattern in a different shape:

- **`/api/transactions/prepare`** (chat-agent writes) ‚Äî fat ~600-line route with inline send/fee/Cetus/Volo PTB-building (NAVI delegated to adapter).
- **`/api/services/prepare`** (MPP `pay_api`) ‚Äî hand-rolled merge/split/transfer pattern, separate from `transactions/prepare`. Three latent bugs caught during the audit (`Math.round` violation, duplicate `client.getCoins`, hand-maintained `allowedAddresses`).
- **`/api/debug-swap`** ‚Äî diagnostic with a parallel Cetus aggregator config that can mislead.
- **PayButton** (`@mysten/payment-kit` + dapp-kit) ‚Äî **intentionally separate** (different signer, different identity, no Enoki). This stays out of `composeTx` by design.

PR-H1 + PR-H4 caught two production bugs in 60 days where someone forgot to add a recipient to the hand-maintained `allowedAddresses` array. That bug class disappears when `allowedAddresses` is auto-derived from the PTB shape inside `composeTx`.

## Forbidden patterns (ESLint enforces ‚Äî `audric/canonical-write` rule, ships in SPEC 7 v0.4)

```typescript
// ‚ùå Direct Transaction construction outside canonical files
import { Transaction } from '@mysten/sui/transactions';
const tx = new Transaction();
// ... merge/split/transfer ...

// ‚ùå Hand-maintained allowedAddresses
const allowedAddresses = [T2000_OVERLAY_FEE_WALLET, params.address, params.recipient];

// ‚ùå Inline coin fetch + merge/split for tx-building
const coins = await client.getCoins({ owner, coinType });
if (coins.data.length > 1) {
  tx.mergeCoins(tx.object(coins.data[0].coinObjectId), ...);
}
const [split] = tx.splitCoins(...);
tx.transferObjects([split], recipient);

// ‚ùå Math.round on raw amount conversion
const rawAmount = BigInt(Math.round(parseFloat(amountUsd) * 10 ** decimals));

// ‚ùå Forking a parallel sponsor flow
const sponsorRes = await fetch('https://api.enoki.mystenlabs.com/v1/transaction-blocks/sponsor', { ... });
```

```typescript
// ‚úÖ Always ‚Äî single composeTx call, single sponsor helper

import { composeTx } from '@t2000/sdk';
import { sponsorViaEnoki } from '@/lib/sponsor';

const composed = await composeTx({
  sender: address,
  steps: [{ toolName: 'send_transfer', input: { to: recipient, amount, asset: 'USDC' } }],
  sponsoredContext: true,
});

const sponsored = await sponsorViaEnoki({
  txKindBytes: composed.txKindBytes,
  sender: address,
  allowedAddresses: composed.derivedAllowedAddresses,
  jwt,
});
```

## Adapter checklist (before adding or modifying any write surface)

1. **Does `composeTx` already cover this write tool?** If yes, use it. Done.
2. **Does it cover it but the tool input shape isn't quite right?** Extend the appender's input contract. Don't fork the route.
3. **Is this a new write tool?** Add a fragment-appender to `@t2000/sdk` (e.g. `addNewToolToTx` in `packages/sdk/src/protocols/new-tool.ts`), wire it into `WRITE_APPENDER_REGISTRY`, then use `composeTx` from the route.
4. **Is the route doing service-specific business logic** (gateway negotiation, balance pre-checks, audit trail, post-payment HTTPS calls)? **Keep that in the route.** Only the on-chain leg goes through `composeTx`. See `services/prepare/route.ts` post-SPEC-7-Layer-0 for the canonical pattern.

If you genuinely need to bypass `composeTx`, leave a `// CANONICAL-BYPASS:` comment with the reason and link to a follow-up issue (or the spec section that documents the exemption). Reviewers gate on this.

