## ESLint rule scope (`audric/canonical-write`)

The rule's include-list is the SINGLE source of truth for "where the contract applies." Files outside the include-list are not lint-checked at all (no need for `// CANONICAL-BYPASS:` comments). Files inside the include-list MUST either route through `composeTx` OR carry a `// CANONICAL-BYPASS: <reason>` comment matching one of the documented bypasses above.

**Include-list:**

```
apps/web-v2/app/api/**/*.ts            // every API route under apps/web-v2 (including app/api/identity/**)
apps/web-v2/components/**/*.tsx        // every React component (PayButton lives here)
apps/web-v2/lib/**/*.ts                // every library helper
```

**Exclude-list** (silent, no enforcement):

```
**/__tests__/**                     // test fixtures
**/*.test.ts                        // unit tests
**/*.spec.ts                        // spec/integration tests
packages/**                         // SDK / engine internals (these define composeTx, not consume it)
scripts/**                          // one-off scripts (smoke-suins-leaf.ts, etc.)
```

**The contract:** if your file is in the include-list and you need to call `new Transaction()` directly, the ONLY legitimate path is a `// CANONICAL-BYPASS: <reason>` comment matching a documented bypass. Do NOT add file-pattern exclusions to widen the silent zone. Reviewers gate on both the comment AND the bypass row in the table above.

## How this is enforced

- **ESLint rule** `audric/canonical-write` (SPEC 7 v0.4 Layer 0 deliverable) ‚Äî fails CI on direct `new Transaction()` outside canonical files; fails on hand-maintained `allowedAddresses` outside the auto-derive path.
- **Spec consistency runner** `lib/engine/spec-consistency.ts` (extended in SPEC 7 v0.4) ‚Äî runs at server startup; dev hard-fails, prod logs. Asserts no parallel write paths exist under `app/api/transactions/` or `app/api/services/`.
- **Contract test** `apps/web/__tests__/composeTx-allowed-addresses.test.ts` (NEW in SPEC 7 v0.4) ‚Äî asserts `derivedAllowedAddresses` matches today's hand-maintained array for every write tool. Fails if a future appender adds a `transferObjects` recipient that wouldn't have been in the hand-maintained list (catches drift immediately).
- **Migration parity test** `apps/web/__tests__/composeTx-migration.test.ts` (NEW in SPEC 7 v0.4) ‚Äî asserts `composeTx({ steps: [{ toolName, input }] })` produces a byte-identical PTB to today's `transactions/prepare` `case toolName` path on a fixed test wallet, for every write tool (12 as of v0.7a Phase 6 ‚Äî `save_deposit`, `withdraw`, `send_transfer`, `borrow`, `repay_debt`, `claim_rewards`, `harvest_rewards`, `pay_api`, `swap_execute`, `volo_stake`, `volo_unstake`, `save_contact`).
- **`services/prepare` parity test** `apps/web/__tests__/services-prepare-parity.test.ts` (NEW in SPEC 7 v0.4) ‚Äî asserts the migrated route returns identical `{ bytes, digest, meta }` shapes for both deliver-first and standard-MPP flows on a fixed test gateway response.

## Special case ‚Äî the engine

Engine write tools (`save_deposit`, `send_transfer`, `swap_execute`, etc.) DON'T directly call `composeTx`. Their `tool.call()` method emits a `pending_action` with `{ toolName, input }`; the audric host calls `composeTx` after the user confirms. This is correct ‚Äî engine carries intent, host owns the on-chain build.

> **Why this matters:** under audric/web's zkLogin trust model, engine `tool.call()` literally never runs in production for confirm-tier writes (the permission gate breaks before `runTools`). Bundling intent (engine) and tx-building (host) is correct. SPEC 7 Layer 0's `composeTx` is the canonical host primitive that consumes engine intent.

For non-zkLogin runtimes (CLI, MCP, server tasks), engine tools DO call `T2000.save()` / `T2000.swap()` / etc. directly ‚Äî these orchestrators in `packages/sdk/src/t2000.ts` will be migrated to compose via `composeTx` internally during SPEC 7 Layer 1 (one canonical primitive across all runtimes).

